      "id": 13,
      "question": "How does HashMap work internally?",
      "section": "Intermediate Level",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
      "tags": [
        "hashmap"
      ],
      "title": "How does HashMap work internally?",
      "sections": [
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "heading": "Introduction",
          "items": [
            "HashMap stores data in an array of buckets.",
            "Each bucket holds Node objects containing key, value, hash, and next.",
            "When put(key, value) is called:",
            "hashCode() of the key is generated.",
            "Bucket index is calculated using (capacity - 1) & hash.",
            "If the bucket is empty, the entry is stored directly.",
            "If a collision occurs:",
            "Keys are compared using equals().",
            "New entries are stored in a LinkedList.",
            "If entries exceed 8, it converts to a Red-Black Tree (Java 8+).",
            "get(key) uses the same hash and index to find the value.",
            "Uses a load factor (0.75) to decide resizing.",
            "When threshold is crossed, capacity doubles and entries are rehashed.",
            "Allows one null key and multiple null values.",
            "Average time complexity for get() and put() is O(1)."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "askedIn": [
        "Google",
        "Amazon"
      ],
